<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-07-12T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-07-12T10:00:00-05:00" n="779" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d779">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">693.119/333: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Crane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-07-12T23:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 12,
                                            1920—11 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 11:50
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>180. Your 169, July 10, 3 p.m. Naval attaché’s report of arms
                                shipment is without doubt correct. Tuan’s<note n="96" xml:id="d779fn96">Gen. Tuan Chih-kuei, commander in chief of the
                                    Anfu army.</note> troops have received these arms. Complaint
                                that Japanese also have shipped arms has been made formally to
                                diplomatic corps by Tsao Kun.<note n="97" xml:id="d779fn97">Inspector general of Chihli, Shantung, and Honan
                                    Provinces.</note></p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>